e-beginning-revenue-secy-123100700594_1.html%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Famp%2Feconomy%2Fnews%2Fonline-gaming-casinos-liable-to-28-gst-since-beginning-revenue-secy-123100700594_1.html%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Courts%20Should%20Deal%20With%20Cases%20Related%20to%20Crimes%20Against%20Women%20in%20a%20Realistic%20Manner%3A%20SC%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F31224356%2FSupreme-Court-II-png.png%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ENew%20Delhi%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20The%20Supreme%20Court%20on%20October%206%20(Friday)%20said%20that%20courts%20should%20deal%20with%20cases%20related%20to%20crimes%20against%20women%20in%20a%20realistic%20manner%2C%20and%20not%20allow%20the%20criminals%20to%20escape%20on%20account%20of%20procedural%20technicalities%2C%20perfunctory%20investigation%2C%20or%20insignificant%20lacunas%20in%20the%20evidence.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EA%20bench%20of%20Justices%20J.B.%20Pardiwala%20and%20Prashant%20Kumar%20Mishra%20made%20these%20remarks%20while%20dismissing%20an%20appeal%20filed%20by%20a%20man%2C%20against%20his%20conviction%2C%20who%20failed%20to%20explain%20what%20had%20happened%20to%20his%20wife%2C%20who%20died%20due%20to%20poisoning.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20bench%20said%20that%20although%20the%20appellant-convict%20tried%20to%20project%20a%20picture%20that%20as%20soon%20as%20his%20wife%20fell%20sick%2C%20he%20immediately%20took%20her%20to%20Delhi%E2%80%99s%20Sanjay%20Gandhi%20%5BMemorial%5D%20Hospital%2C%20there%20is%20no%20evidence%20in%20this%20regard%2C%20the%20bench%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThe%20appellant-convict%20was%20expected%20to%20lead%20some%20evidence%20as%20to%20what%20had%20transpired%20at%20Sanjay%20Gandhi%20Hospital.%20He%20has%20maintained%20complete%20silence.%20It%20is%20only%20the%20appellant-convict%20who%20could%20have%20explained%20in%20what%20circumstances%20and%20in%20what%20manner%20he%20had%20taken%20his%20wife%20to%20the%20hospital%20and%20who%20attended%20his%20wife%20at%20the%20hospital.%20If%20it%20is%20his%20case%20that%20his%20wife%20was%20declared%20dead%20on%20being%20brought%20to%20the%20hospital%2C%20then%20it%20is%20difficult%20to%20believe%20that%20the%20hospital%20authorities%20allowed%20the%20appellant%20to%20carry%20the%20dead%20body%20back%20home%20without%20completing%20the%20legal%20formalities%2C%E2%80%9D%20said%20Justice%20Pardiwala.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20bench%20said%20that%20there%20is%20sufficient%20circumstantial%20evidence%20to%20enable%20the%20prosecution%20to%20invoke%20Section%20106%20of%20the%20Evidence%20Act%20(w%3Cspan%20lang%3D%5C%22en%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3Ehen%20any%20fact%20is%20especially%20within%20the%20knowledge%20of%20any%20person%2C%20the%20burden%20of%20proving%20that%20fact%20is%20upon%20him%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E)%20and%20shift%20the%20burden%20on%20the%20accused%20husband%20to%20explain%20what%20had%20actually%20happened%20on%20the%20date%20his%20wife%20died.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20word%C2%A0%20%E2%80%9Cespecially%E2%80%9D%2C%20the%20bench%20explained%2C%20means%20facts%20that%20are%20preeminently%20or%20exceptionally%20within%20the%20knowledge%20of%20the%20accused.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESection%20106%20is%20an%20exception%20to%20Section%20101%20of%20the%20Evidence%20Act.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESection%20101%20lays%20down%20the%20general%20rule%20that%2C%20in%20a%20criminal%20case%2C%20the%20burden%20of%20proof%20is%20on%20the%20prosecution%2C%20and%20Section%20106%20is%20by%20no%20means%20intended%20to%20relieve%20it%20of%20that%20duty.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EOn%20the%20contrary%2C%20the%20bench%20said%20that%20Section%20106%20is%20designed%20to%20address%20specific%20exceptional%20circumstances%20in%20which%20it%20might%20be%20impossible%20or%2C%20at%20the%20very%20least%2C%20excessively%20burdensome%20for%20the%20prosecution%20to%20substantiate%20facts%20that%20are%20%E2%80%9Cespecially%20within%20the%20knowledge%20of%20the%20accused%20and%20which%20he%20can%20prove%20without%20difficulty%20or%20inconvenience.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ECiting%20several%20cases%2C%20the%20bench%20held%20that%20the%20court%20should%20apply%20Section%20106%20of%20the%20Evidence%20Act%20in%20criminal%20cases%20with%20care%20and%20caution.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CIt%20cannot%20be%20said%20that%20it%20has%20no%20application%20to%20criminal%20cases.%20The%20ordinary%20rule%20which%20applies%20to%20criminal%20trials%20in%20this%20country%2C%20that%20the%20onus%20lies%20on%20the%20prosecution%20to%20prove%20the%20guilt%20of%20the%20accused%2C%20is%20not%20in%20any%20way%20modified%20by%20the%20provisions%20contained%20in%20Section%20106%20of%20the%20Evidence%20Act%2C%E2%80%9D%20observed%20the%20bench.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20bench%20clarified%20that%20Section%20106%20cannot%20be%20invoked%20to%20make%20up%20for%20the%20inability%20of%20the%20prosecution%20to%20produce%20evidence%20of%20circumstances%20pointing%20to%20the%20guilt%20of%20the%20accused.%20This%20section%20cannot%20be%20used%20to%20support%20a%20conviction%20unless%20the%20prosecution%20has%20discharged%20the%20onus%20by%20proving%20all%20the%20elements%20necessary%20to%20establish%20the%20offence%2C%20it%20held.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20bench%20further%20clarified%20that%20the%20onus%20does%20not%20shift%20to%20the%20accused%20until%20a%20prima%20facie%20case%20is%20established%20by%20such%20circumstantial%20evidence.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESection%20106%20pertains%20to%20cases%20where%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%20guilt%20is%20established%20based%20on%20the%20evidence%20presented%20by%20the%20prosecution%2C%20unless%20the%20accused%20can%20provide%20additional%20facts%2C%20particularly%20within%20their%20knowledge%2C%20that%20would%20negate%20the%20prosecution%E2%80%99s%20evidence%2C%20the%20bench%20explained.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20such%20a%20scenario%2C%20if%20the%20accused%20provides%20an%20explanation%20that%20is%20reasonably%20true%20considering%20the%20proven%20circumstances%2C%20they%20benefit%20from%20the%20principle%20of%20reasonable%20doubt%2C%20even%20if%20they%20cannot%20prove%20the%20truth%20of%20their%20explanation%20beyond%20a%20reasonable%20doubt%2C%20said%20the%20bench.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20if%20the%20accused%20fails%20to%20provide%20any%20explanation%20or%20provides%20a%20false%20or%20untenable%20explanation%2C%20this%20alone%20may%20turn%20the%20scale%20against%20them%2C%20it%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20present%20case%2C%20considering%20the%20proved%20facts%2C%20the%20bench%20said%20it%20is%20unable%20to%20speculate%20about%20any%20alternative%20theory%20which%20is%20compatible%20with%20the%20innocence%20of%20the%20accused.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20the%20bench%20reduced%20the%20sentence%20of%20the%20deceased%E2%80%99s%20mother-in-law%2C%20who%20is%20convicted%20only%20for%20the%20offence%20punishable%20under%20Section%20498-A%20of%20the%20Indian%20Penal%20Code%20(dealing%20with%20punishment%20for%20husband%20or%20his%20relative%20subjecting%20a%20woman%20to%20cruelty)%2C%20to%20the%20period%20already%20undergone.%20As%20she%20is%20on%20bail%2C%20the%20bench%20said%20she%20is%20not%20required%20to%20surrender%20at%20the%20moment.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20bench%20argued%20that%20courts%20should%20approach%20cases%20related%20to%20women%20in%20a%20more%20realistic%20manner.%20Otherwise%2C%20it%20could%20lead%20to%20criminals%20being%20encouraged%20while%20discouraging%20the%20victims%20due%20to%20the%20lack%20of%20punishment%20for%20the%20crimes.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1696679117000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F31224356%2FSupreme-Court-II-png.png%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Flaw%2Fcourts-should-deal-with-cases-related-to-crimes-against-women-in-a-realistic-manner-sc%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Courts%20should%20not%20allow%20the%20criminals%20to%20escape%20on%20account%20of%20proc